wool away
Homonym Number:
Word Class:exclamation
Sense Number: 1
Definition:a call made to pickers-up by shearers about to send a shorn sheep down the port-hole or requiring pieces, bellies or locks to be swept away before a fleece is completely shorn.
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1897
Source: Station Ballads
Author: McKEE WRIGHT
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: `All aboard! All aboard!' is the cry./ They're a ripping lot of shearers in the shed;/ ... /`Wool away! Wool away!' is the cry/ And the merry game of busting is begun!/ They're going sheep and sheep, for Big Mick will do or die,/ And the fleecy boys are kept upon the run./ ... /[fn] In old-time sheds these calls indicated the beginning and of a run.
Notes: 1897 McKee Wright Station Ballads `Shearing' in 1950 Woodhouse Farm and Station Verse 33

